Republican Resistance Strategy for the Re-Elect of Obama
Republican leaders justified their policies by the need to combat election fraud.
However, the Brennan Center considers the latter a myth, arguing that cases of falsifications in elections in the United States are more rare than deaths from a lightning strike.
In addition, Republican lawyers counted only 300 cases of electoral fraud in the United States in ten years.
One thing is certain: these new trends will have a negative impact on voter turnout.
In this sense, such actions partially discredit the system of American democracy.
Unlike Canada, American states are responsible for organizing federal elections in the United States.
That is why most state governments have been enacting laws that complicate the process of registration or voting since 2009.
This phenomenon received a new scale after the November 2010 elections, which brought Republicans 675 new seats in 26 states.
As a result, in just one year 2011, 180 bills were passed, limiting the right to vote in 41 states.
The new election laws require the voter to present an identity card with a photo and proof of the presence of American citizenship.
In addition, these laws reduce the period of early voting, abolish the right to register the voter on the day of the will and take away the right to vote from citizens with a criminal record.
Until the 2006 election, no U.S. state required voters to show a photo ID.
Indiana became the first state to introduce such a claim.
The U.S. Supreme Court confirmed in 2008 the constitutionality of the law passed in Indiana.
The Republican authorities hastened to extend this practice to other states.
Over the past two years, they have initiated bills obliging voters to present identity cards with a photo in 34 states.
It is important to note that unlike Quebec, American citizens do not have such a universal identity card as a health insurance card.
Indeed, 11% of U.S. citizens, that is, 21 million people who have reached the voting age, do not have an identity card with a photo issued by their state’s government authority.
In addition, five million new voters in 2012 do not have such a document.
At the same time, the cost of obtaining the required ID card often exceeds one hundred dollars.
The new restrictions disproportionately affect young people, minorities and people with low incomes.
In fact, 25% of African Americans, 15% of people earning less than 35,000, 18% of citizens over 65 years old, and 20% of voters 18 to 29 years old do not have the required ID with a photo.
But that's not all.
Students – voters who are believed to vote for Democratic candidates are not allowed in several states to use a photo ID issued by their educational institution.
But these same states allow members of fishing and hunting clubs who vote mainly for Republicans to use certificates issued by these clubs to vote.
Until 2004, no state required evidence of the existence of American voting citizenship.
For the first time, such a requirement was introduced in Arizona.
Since 2011, more than ten states have passed laws requiring voters to prove that they are U.S. citizens.
These measures are obviously aimed at limiting the vote of Latin American people.
It is estimated that two-thirds of Latin American voters vote in favor of the Democratic Party.
In addition, Republican lawmakers initiated in 2011 laws abolishing voter registration on the day of voting in eight states.
They also restricted the right of individuals or groups to assist those who wish to register.
This limitation did not pass without consequences.
For example, during the 2004 elections, the voter registration campaign helped to list about 10 million citizens.
At the same time, measures taken since 2009 have led to a 17% drop in the level of registration of new voters in 2010 compared to 2006.
In addition, Republican lawmakers have passed in five other states laws aimed at reducing the period of early voting.
So, during the 2008 general election in Florida, 33% of voters who voted early were African-American, although the latter accounted for only 13% of the total number of voters in the state.
The same thing happened with Latin America.
Representing only 11% of voters, they accounted for 24% of citizens who voted early.
Unlike whites, which, forming 76% of voters, among voters were early only 46%.
Of course, Democratic legislators and their supporters are actively opposed to the adoption of laws restricting the registration of voters.
Several draft laws were vetoed by Democratic governors.
The most ambiguous laws were suspended by the intervention of the Attorney General of the United States.
This has partially limited negative consequences.
For example, only 16 of the 34 states have passed laws requiring a photo identification certificate.
However, the new rules that have entered into force will certainly make it difficult to exercise the suffrage in the 2012 elections.
Democratic critics condemn the bias of the laws that have been passed, seeing them as an obvious focus on influencing the results of the 2012 election in key states.
The 2011 Brennan Center’s report shows that the states that have passed these laws represent 171 of the 270 votes required in the electoral college to win the presidential election.
It is too early to say with certainty that these legislative changes at the electoral level will have a significant impact on the results of the 2012 presidential election.
Only one thing is certain: these new provisions will have a negative impact on the turnout of voters.
In this sense, such actions partially discredit the system of American democracy.
