Higgs Boson in Detail
Last summer, the announcement that scientists may have discovered the Higgs boson caused a real stir – and not without reason.
It is believed that this boson explains the mass of all particles in the universe, no less.
In addition, it is the last particle, the existence of which was predicted within the framework of the Standard Model - our best, or, at least "the least imperfect" description of the nature and behavior of matter - but which before could not be detected by experimental means.
But physicists are not yet fully sure that we are talking about the Higgs boson.
We know, without a shadow of a doubt that we are dealing with a really new particle and that it strongly resembles the Higgs boson predicted by the Standard Model.
In addition, the new data presented this week at a major physical congress in Kyoto seems to confirm this, although some data is still lacking for full confidence.
Let’s imagine that we are talking about the Higgs boson, since the chances of making a mistake seem minimal, and let’s see what it means.
There is, in this world, one law is completely inevitable, which says that two things cannot be in the same place at the same time.
There is no way to circumvent this rule, do not even try too hard, otherwise harm yourself.
But although the physics of elementary particles is a rather strange world, it turns out that it also has one law of this nature: the principle of Pauli, which postulates that two particles cannot occupy the same space at the same time, if they are in the same “quantum state” – this “state” is, in general terms, in some of their characteristics.
Based on this, physicists divide particles into two categories.
In one corner, we find good citizens called ferrios, who prudently obey the Pauli principle.
In the other, the bosons, the nefarious gang of anarchists, who have no respect for nothing - at least to this principle, which means that they can calmly be in the same place at the same time.
According to the site (bite, completely extraordinary) Particle Adventure of the Berkeley Laboratory, these bosons are divided, in turn, into two groups: mesons, which we will not talk about here, and the “force particles” through which the main forces of nature are spread and to which the Higgs boson relates in some way.
These very bosons, it should be emphasized, not all such exotic creatures as one would think.
In fact, if you manage to read this chronicle, it is thanks to one incredibly banal boson: a photon, or a “light particle” that is the “courier” of electromagnetic force.
In fact, when one particle with an electric charge is accelerated or altered direction, it “disturbs” the electromagnetic field in this particular location, roughly like a stone thrown into the pond.
From this "violation" is born an electromagnetic wave (light, or infrared radiation, or ultraviolet radiation, etc. d.), and this wave is nothing but a photon - and, therefore, one of the bosons of "transferents".
A more stable field
The same thing happens with the Higgs boson, with the only difference that in order for this boson to appear, another field, the Higgs field, the Higgs field, should be “disturbed”.
However, the Higgs field is much much, much more stable than the electromagnetic field; in order to excite it, it is necessary to achieve very, very high energies, as if it was about a frozen pond, the surface of which could only shake a very large stone.
That is why you need a huge particle accelerator, like the one that is operated in CERN - the Large Hadron Collider, which is a ring with a diameter of 27 km! - to achieve such huge energies.
An analogy with an electromagnetic field is also useful for explaining the ratio between the Higgs boson and the mass.
In fact, not all particles and not all materials interact with the electromagnetic field.
Some, like magnets, interact, others do not: a piece of paper, for example, will never hold on the refrigerator.
Similarly, not all particles interact with the Higgs field: those that interact have mass, while others (as a photon, by the way), do not have it.
So, what "can bring" all these studies, asks Ms. Plamondon?
In science, they are used to test the correctness of the Standard Model (CM), and this also allows physicists to find a discrepancy between observations and CM predictions.
In addition, some of them are passionate about such a divergence to be found. c. The slightest discrepancy can open the door for the “new physics” and shut down some of the Model’s holes.
The latter, I must say, still has significant drawbacks, offering no explanation for gravity (oh!) or for dark matter, which forms about 80% of the universe (oh!).
But so far, such discrepancies have not been found in CERN.
Consequences
The benefit of these studies for the daily life of the average person is more difficult to predict, but it would be a mistake to assume that it is not.
See: in the early 60's, the pioneers of laser research in Bell's laboratories could not even imagine what kind of revolution their work will cause.
They foresaw their applications in science, but nothing more.
Indeed, the late physicist Willard Boyle, who worked in Bell Labs, where a laser was invented in 1960, and who himself developed the first continuous laser (previous were pulsed) in 1962, said that the laser was originally seen as a “laboratory gadget.”
Imagine...
In addition, the application can be found for the tools accompanying the study.
For example, the same Williard Boyle developed a small light sensor during his optical research in 1969.
This sensor, although it was not its original purpose, now serves as an “eye” for all the digital cameras in the world and earned the Nobel Prize in physics in 2009.
This, of course, does not mean that the work of the Grand Hadron Colliderar will definitely change our lives, but it only shows, in fact, that everything can be.
