53% of patients admitted to the Victoria-Gadbua shelter come from home, and 47% from the hospital.
The Problem of Access to Palliative Care
It is estimated that 77% of Canadians simply do not have access to palliative care, that is, care, which is provided to alleviate the suffering of patients who have entered the final stage of their lives, whether at home, in the hospital or in the shelter.
And some institutions, such as the Victor Ghadboua Shelter and the Society for Palliative Care at the Home of Greater Montreal, specialize more or less exclusively in the care of cancer patients.
It is this large gap in the health care system of Quebec that forces many doctors - specialists in palliative care to fear the adoption of a law that legalizes euthanasia and self-suicide care.
