Recently, she says, “I saw a patient who spent 14 days in the emergency room, in terrible pain, and no one took the necessary measures to alleviate them.
I am afraid that patients want to die just because they do not receive adequate care.
At the same time, many oncologists until the last day try to save patients, despite pessimistic prognosis.
The expectations of Helene Richard’s survival were already minimal when she stopped debilitating chemotherapy.
When I told my oncologist that I was stopping treatment, she told me that she regretted that I was stopping the fight, she says.
She told me that my days were numbered!
There is no all-powerful care
Dr. Martel believes that 90% of patients who ask for death, thank the medical staff, for not fulfilling their request, after the palliative care team relieves their pain.
However, it should be noted that palliative care is not absolutely all-powerful in the fight against pain.
According to Elsie Monroe, director of palliative care at the Household of Palliative Care at the Greater Montreal House, patients are not susceptible to pain relief in 8% of cases.
At the very end of life, doctors often resort to palliative sedation, in which the patient sleeps until his death, either from time to time or constantly.
It is impossible to pretend that we do not know about this suffering.
Increasingly, patients who fail to relieve pain can have access to palliative sedation.
Patients suffering from pain always say the same phrase: “I want to die.”
But that doesn’t necessarily mean “I want to be euthanasiaded for me,” it means “I want to make me feel better.”
