Paying and selling without the help of banks - with Bitcoin
The complete opposite of the current monetary exchange, based on central banks, numbered transactions between the receiving parties with commission fees for their processing.
In addition, as often happens to these technologies, it is obvious a political vision: the belief that the current monetary system, consisting of bank monopolies, leads to financial crises.
In fact, Bitcoin, invented by Satoshi Nakamoto (pseudonie), is also a virtual currency (but convertible into dollars, euros ...) and a secure BitTorrent-type exchange protocol that allows you to exchange files between participants of the same level.
About 200 000 operations have already been registered with 15 000 computers in the network.
Several thousand sites accept bitcoins to make donations or as a means of payment.
The bitcoin exchange rate, reaching a top of $30 (€23) in June 2011, five months later fell to $2 before returning to about ten dollars today (the rates are listed on the bitcoincharts.com website).
Nothing special in comparison with the world exchange of real money or financial products.
However, the European Central Bank (ECB) in its report on virtual currency, published in October, became interested in this system.
He describes bitcoin as “the most successful virtual currency”, “competing with the dollar or the euro” and “similar to conventional currencies”.
Bitcoin differs from other types of virtual currencies, such as “loans” used to promote in a video game that are earned during the game or that can be bought (and sometimes exchange).
Facebook has also developed a similar system.
But exchange operations always control and processes a central organ.
In Bitcoin, all network nodes are simultaneously holders of the ledger, auditors, currency issuers, buyers and sellers.
How does this network work?
Each transaction between two users actually occurs between two email addresses, like email.
Only for each new payment, the user can choose another address, thus ensuring anonymity.
The set of information related to this transaction is signed electronically, using a dual key encryption system.
The network can also verify the authenticity of the transaction.
Thanks to the content of the file, it is possible to check what the bitcoins used in the transaction do exist in a public account book sent throughout the network.
The key step is to register a new transaction in this book.
It goes through the solution of a mathematical problem sent to computers, which, like a temporary central bank, receives a privilege to add this new line.
We are talking about the file hash phase, that is, the transformation of a large file into a digital signature, short and unique.
Computers "take" a new transaction and add a number to it before "hapch" all together.
The goal is to find a number that will give a unique digital signature (a lot of zeros at the beginning).
Once this number is found, other nodes easily check that it is correct.
The transaction thus turns out to be inextricably linked to the chain of all other transactions; any modification will change the digital signature.
If, for the purpose of deception, the user very quickly (less than ten minutes) would wish to pay twice the same topic with money, only one of these two transactions would be confirmed by the network - and the other would be unconfirmed, since they have different electronic signatures.
The computer that solved the problem receives 50 bitcoins.
To avoid inflation, the award regularly shares in half, probably until the end of 2012.
The number of bitcoins in circulation is therefore limited to 21 million, but they are divided to one hundred millionth, which leaves another reserve.
The complexity of the task also increases with the increase in computing power.
The life of the network has already experienced ups and downs.
Sites providing Bitcoin services were attacked, and bitcoins were stolen from reserves.
“The used defect does not apply to the protocol itself,” assures Pierre Noisa, who recently launched Paymium, a company that makes payments with real money using the Bitcoin network.
The ECB also reported on the possibility of money laundering through this anonymous service.
But cash also has this drawback.
Large players such as Wikipedia refuse to accept donations of this kind.
Others, such as the WordPress blog platform, allow them.
Recently, Adi Shamir and Dorit Ron of the Weizmann Institute in Israel, analyzed the counting book and found that almost 80% of bitcoins are not in circulation.
"Giant sales" were announced in November.
“Thirty thousand dollars have been exchanged,” Jone Holmqvist, who works at Coinabul, who converts bitcoin into gold, rejoices.
Pierre Nuaz, another author of this currency manual, firmly believes in the potential of this technology as an operating network.
Its system, Paytunia, is the equivalent of a credit card (in real money) or contactless payment via a mobile phone, but it uses Bitcoin to verify transactions, which is cheaper in this way.
The holder controls his personal data better and may thus be anonymous.
The system is simple in implementation for entrepreneurs who do not need to install new devices or software.
It is enough just to tell the address that can be “photoed and recognized” by phone, says Pierre Noise, assuring that he already has thousands of users.
There is a general tendency to revise hierarchical systems in favor of more horizontal ones.
“Betweden, before the firmware, it will take some time, but 2013 could be a turning point,” he predicts.
