Poland and Space.
Last week, at a meeting of ministers of the European Space Agency, Poland was adopted by the twentieth member of the European Space Agency as the second country from the former Eastern bloc (after the Czech Republic, which became a full member of ESA on September 12, 2008).
Poland began close cooperation with ESA in 1994 and for the following years took an active part in a number of projects of the agency.
But the path to space Poland began much earlier.
Even before World War II, Polish enthusiasts were engaged in flights to space, but this did not always meet with understanding.
Let me remind you, for example, the lecture A. Sternfeld, who on December 6, 1933, presented in the Warsaw Astronomical Observatory ideas from his pioneering work "Introduction to Cooperatives".
Ideas of a Young Engineer (1905) left the audience indifferent, after several years Sternfeld recalled that only Dr. Jan Gadomski was interested in his work.
In 1934, in France, Sternfeld won the Robert Ence-Peltree Prize and André Luis Hirsch for Introducing Cosmonautics.
Dr. Jan Gadomskie (1899-1966), which was mentioned above, later became a great propagandist of astronomy and cosmonautics.
He published hundreds of articles in Polish journals and wrote a number of books on these scientific disciplines.
Gadomski became a world-renowned space propagandist, and his contribution was appreciated, among other things, that one of the craters on the far side of the moon was named in his honor.
Already in 1925, a railway tribe equipped with a rocket engine was built in Poland.
Unfortunately, the author of this idea remained unknown, as well as the details of the project.
It is not even clear whether a missile was to be used to disperse or for braking the trolley.
Information about this tyre is known only from the press of that era.
Since 1933, Polish artillery began to think about rocket arrows.
The study was carried out by the Arms Engineering Section in cooperation with Professors Mecislav Wolfk and Gustav Mokzyk.
From the surviving materials it can be seen that the research has reached the stage of practical testing.
But with the arrival of the German troops, the work was interrupted.
In 1937, the intended printing appeared the idea of a photovoltaic fighter rocket, which was proposed by engineer Rogozinsky, and the next year the work of the Air Torpedo and the Air Rocket-Bomb Aircraft by Levilya-Kvizhiblobitsky was released.
Both projects were developed for the military use of rocket engines.
Before the war, all the projects of military use of missile technology were carried out by the Temporary Scientific Advisory Committee (Tymczaowy Komitet Doradzo-Naukowy), which coordinated all the work.
The committee was established in 1937, but after two years of its activity, the work ended due to the outbreak of war.
The next scientific work on cosmonautics appeared in the Polish press after the war, thanks to the work of the Polish Astronautics Society (Polskie Towarzystwo Astronautyczne).
For the first time, the society is mentioned in the November issue of 1954 of the magazine "Problems", which publishes four voluminous articles on astronautics.
In one of them, Professor M. Subotovich proposed to organize a society that will deal with space exploration.
At that time, projects of artificial satellites were already gaining momentum, and it was clear that space research is a promising industry.
Since the beginning of 1956, the Polish Astronautical Society (POA) has tried to join the international federation of astronautics (founded in 1951), and in the autumn of POA became a full member.
And the following year, the first chairman of the POA, Kazimierz Zarankevich (1902 - 1959), became deputy chairman of the International Astronautics Federation.
In this position he remained until his death, which came in 1959.
Since 1956, the POA has made a significant contribution to the development of the very successful RM (Rakieta Meteorologiczna) meteorological rocket, which became the first Polish missile to carry out a scientific study.
The first type of RM-1 was completed in 1957, and the first launch took place on October 10, 1958.
The rocket, capable of covering a distance of 1800 m, was about 80 cm long, and its weight was less than 5 kg.
Subsequently, an improved version of the RM-1A was built, and in the summer of 1959, a two-stage RM-2 missile was tested on the Bledovsky Darylum.
This missile was about 1.4 m long, and its weight was about 11.5 kg.
The next version of the rocket was already able to do real scientific work - the RM-34 missile could overcome 14.5 km, and its task was to monitor the high-altitude wind.
But in 1962, further development was suspended.
The heir to the first RM missiles was a Meteor-1 rocket developed between 1962 and 1965.
The missile was conceived as a two-stage, its total length was 510 cm, and the initial weight was 32.5 kg.
Three types (designated as Meteor-1A, -1B and -1C) were developed, which differed in the size of the chamber for scientific equipment.
The Meteor-1A missile had a space of 0.4 liters, Meteor-1V - 0.34 liters, and Meteor-1S - 0.62l.
The maximum flight range of all three types was 37 km.
Between 1965 and 1968, the Meteor 2 rocket was developed at the Aviation Institute, and its first flight tests began in October 1970.
The Meteor-2 rocket with a starting weight of 380 kg was able to bring a payload weighing 10 kg to a height of about 60 km.
Then the Meteor-2N and Meteor-3 versions were built.
It is also worth mentioning the entry of Poland into the COSPAR (Committee on Space Research) in 1960 and the establishment of the national committee of COSPAR two years later.
In addition, as part of the Intercosmos program, Poland participated in space exploration on Soviet artificial satellites, and in 1978, Polish pilot Miroslav Germashevsky became the second intercostorium after Vladimir Remek.
