"Operation Argo": When there is nowhere worse, call Hollywood
In November 1979, a crowd of Islamist demonstrators captured the U.S. Embassy in Tehran and took 52 diplomats hostage.
They were to be released in exchange for the deposed Shah Mohammed Reza Pahlavi, who fled after the U.S. revolution, who had been the patron saint of his regime for decades.
For the US administration, there was no positive outcome of the situation - it could not afford to throw the Shah overboard, because it could fundamentally undermine the trust of allies in other countries.
However, it was not able to achieve the release of the hostages in Iran, where the revolution led to the establishment of a theocratic regime.
It was a blow to the prestige of the United States, which was later reinforced by an unsuccessful attempt to free the hostages by force.
The imprisoned diplomats were finally released after 444 days, after negotiations through the mediation of the Algerian government.
Their fate caused the houses a wave of solidarity and anti-Iranian sentiments.
The defeat in Iran largely contributed to the defeat of Jimmy Carter in the 1980 presidential election, which ended with the election of Ronald Reagan.
The film, directed by actor Ben Affleck "Operation Argo" describes one of the episodes of the story that brought America small victories.
Shortly before the occupation of the embassy, six workers managed to escape.
After difficult vicissitudes, they finished their journey at the residence of the Embassy of Canada.
The CIA, in collaboration with the Canadian authorities, managed to take them out of Iran, with an extravagant organ of cover, according to which they went on Canadian passports as members of the crew, looking for a place in the country for the filming of a science fiction epic.
Combination of genres
The plan, which was invented by the expert on “evacuation” Tony Mendes, demanded cooperation between Hollywood.
In order for the legend to be reliable, in specialized magazines it was written about the project of the film, press conferences were arranged, a fictional production company had a real office.
Details of the operation for a long time kept secret, the film, based on the memoirs of Tony Mendes.
Affleck's film is a special combination of several genres.
On the one hand, a real political thriller, the so-called "film-cinepas", the story of a successful idea, a scam - an example can be a number of films about Owsen's friends.
The film constantly changing moods - on the one hand, documented scenes from Tehran (credits show iconic historical photos of events and how the same situations were demonstrated in the film - there are no big differences in this).
On the other hand, lightweight Hollywood passages intersecting with irony and moderate exaggeration.
And then scenes from the headquarters of the CIA and other institutions - men in costumes discuss the situation at the negotiating tables, on the stairs of institutions, on the phone ...
Ben Affleck managed to make a career restart.
From the ridiculed actor became a respected director, and his game ceased to be the object of ridicule.
"Operation Argo" his third feature film, after the dark detective "Goodbye, Baby, Goodbye" (2007) and Thriller "City" (2010).
At the same time, this is the first Affleck film, which is not shot in the director's hometown - Boston.
The feeling of the atmosphere of the place at the same time refers to the qualities that elevated earlier films of the director over the Hollywood standard.
And Affleck shows this in Argo, where Tehran is “playing” Canada.
The best scenes in the film take place on the streets, during the reconstruction of real events - the introductory scenes of the fall of the embassy impress with their clarity, which also conveys the emotions of confusion and unforeseenness that arise when the story suddenly changes somewhere suddenly.
Affleck and his colleagues achieve a similar effect in the stages of fictional (fake headquarters at the Tegeran Bazaar).
Too many processes in too many places.
The director had to deal with the fact that the narrative does not involve many exciting scenes of cinematic significance.
He works quite successfully with this few, sometimes thinks something - all this does not go so elegantly (the scene in which a phone call in America prevents the impending crisis at the airport of Tehran, and the pursuit of the runway looks quite far-fetched).
The disadvantage of Argo is the lack of distraction associated with the need to show too many events in too many places.
Alan Arkin and John Goodman as Hollywood colleagues are really very charming, but their characters would deserve more space, and they are not the only ones in the film.
Affleck’s film lacks a bit of drama, a film that can be watched with moderate interest, evaluating the production and retro style, reassigning the thrillers of the seventies.
But it's hard to get involved.
However, this is enough to remind one, still in a certain sense of living history, as well as to testimonies to how the ideas about the omnipotent and omniscient special services are exaggerated.
