MVRDV architects prove that real adventures are not only in the imagination - on the example of Spikenisse and its newly built Book Mountain - 2 photos
“It seems to me that building seems fun, it looks futuristic, finally we can see something interesting again,” says Lisette Verheig, a passerby on the edge of the road.
And Stefan Spermont, an IT specialist at a nearby large enterprise, said: "No, this building is really beautiful."
But I ask myself: why do we need another library today?
Everyone has the Internet, iPad and e-books.
Now no one voluntarily goes to such old-fashioned libraries, right?
Speykenisse, a unremarkable sleeping town near Rotterdam, owns an unusual record.
Its population of 80,000 has the lowest level of education in the Netherlands.
To combat this annoying circumstance a few years ago, it was decided to contribute to the general education and build seven fictional bridges, which are depicted on euro banknotes, in the form of picturesquely painted miniatures made of reinforced concrete.
The success of this educational initiative was modest.
And then the fathers of the city realized that they had the only opportunity to overcome the statistics: to build a library here!
Viny Maas from the Rotterdam Architecture MVRDV, a master of bold column diagrams and the author of witty, sometimes even cynical buildings, treated the task with his usual equanimity and appeared at a competitive audition in 2003 with five books under the arm and a smirk on his face.
And while the jury members were puzzled and shrugging, the daring Maas folded a pyramid in size from his original gift and completed a speech in defense of his project with the following words: “Dear citizens!”
Here it is, my sentence: "Book Mountain" in Spakenis, the so-called Bukenberg!
Nine years later, this 30 millionth mountain has grown.
It is part of the revitalization project, which also includes an underground garage, a supermarket, a post office and several adjacent houses and townhouses for a total of 50 apartments.
In early November, the "Book Mountain" was awarded the second prize of the contest "Best Library of the Netherlands 2012".
The project also participates in the national Dutch competition of wooden structures in 2012.
Thus, the faceless suburb, which previously could not offer anything but the postmodern pedestrian zone and the surprisingly ugly town hall, the white facades of which suggest the idea of the dairy plant, became richer in one modern work of architecture.
But most importantly, in Spakenis appeared the first in the history of this town public building for cultural purpose.
The Long Way to the Book
First impression: the book Eldorado under the hood for cheese.
There is only one elevator that passes in the center of the mountain range, because real fans of architecture and readings will prefer to explore this area on foot.
Glazed on all sides of the room - bright and easily foreseeable, the floors made of burnt brick and elegant street lights unmistakably create a sense of public urban area.
The urban environment is perfectly recreated.
The look is involuntarily looking for benches, dogs and football-playing boys and girls.
And everywhere - books, books, books.
“Usually book shelves stand along the facades, and in the middle there is a large dark hall, usually uncomfortable and faceless,” says Viny Maas.
We put the classical configuration of the space on the head and pulled the area to read from the inside out.
The interior of the book mountain is used skillfully: the center houses offices, an Internet library, a chess club, an environmental center and technical rooms.
Especially pleasing is the black bookshelves that serve as the decoration of the walls, then parapets, then stairwells.
Their appearance, texture and smell are unusual.
Even sophisticated architects and civil engineers are lost in guessing what kind of unknown material it is.
“We sought to work with secondary materials,” explains Jop Traubrest, project manager representing the Spikenisse community, in accordance with the requirements of the standard.
And once at one agricultural enterprise in Friesland, we met a suitable by-product of agriculture.
For many years in greenhouses and in the fields in the Netherlands as a lining for roots used artificial fibrous material of millimeter thickness.
It is cheap and saves time.
Subtle textiles last one or two seasons, after that it can be discarded.
For the library, this canvas - for the first time in such volumes - was compressed in a four-centered panel.
Under the influence of heat and pressure, the so-called Landbachoplast (KLP) turns into a dark, homogeneous, durable material, smelling a little resembling a new car and a little sneakers.
There are 105 steps to the top.
Whoever overcomes the path of almost 500 meters long will be rewarded in a literary cafe not only a fantastic view of the city, but also Dutch croquet and tree ficus in pots.
They care about the atmosphere, and first of all about the correct humidity of the air on the literary mountain.
Costs of a New Soul
“It’s hard to believe, but this building, despite many glass surfaces, is an exemplary project in terms of ecology,” says Troubrest.
For its heating and cooling, the heat of the earth is used.
Although the Book Mountain stands under a glass cap, even on clear days the sun gets inside only for a while.
Wide glued wood farms, located perpendicular to the glass facade, give shade and take on most of the sun's rays.
The climate in the room is very pleasant.
The rest of the protection is provided by fully automatic roller blinds.
Stefan Spermon, mentioned above the skeptic from the IT sector, has already visited the new library.
Lisette Verheig was already here.
As well as the teacher of traditional Chinese medicine Cinny Bogard, who called Buckenberg “the soul of Spakenis, which has long been lacking.”
Reason: A few weeks before the opening, each resident received an invitation to donate one book from his own collection.
These books were to take empty places on the shelves of the not yet fully staffed library - at that time there were 70,000 books in it.
The idea worked.
The shelves are forced to the top.
“There’s nothing worse than a half-empty library,” says architect Vinny Maas.
“I think that thanks to our invitation, every resident is now connected in some way with this new home.
Everyone knows that his book is part of this building.
Even if it serves only for decoration.
Thus, MVRDV managed to solve the royal problem, which in professional jargon is called the creation of identity.
Spakenis wrote his literary story.
And let them be very young and uneducated.
This is only the starting point for building an identity.
Stake: "The Germans have to play a more important role"
Germany abstained in the vote on the recognition of Palestine.
According to Stephen Szabo, an expert on relations between the United States and Europe, doing so, Berlin balances on a narrow diplomatic path.
Deutsche Welle: At the beginning of the week, Germany first made it clear that it would vote against the Palestinian bid to obtain observer status at the United Nations.
But then Berlin abstained in the vote.
Why?
Stephen Szabo: Germany does not support the actions of the Israelis in Gaza.
Germany needs to be careful in connection with its special relationship with Israel.
But at the same time, I believe that she does not support the American position either.
Germany wanted to demonstrate its independence - without speaking too critically towards Israel.
During the uprising in Libya in March 2011, Germany also abstained in the voting on the introduction of a no-fly zone for flights.
As a result, NATO made this proposal.
Is Germany difficult to take a clear position on complex international issues?
Yeah, that's right.
The fact is that it is in the process of transforming its foreign policy, namely, it is moving from a policy that, so to speak, was governed by the United States, to German foreign policy itself.
In addition, the situation is complicated by the fact that Europeans do not have a coherent unified policy.
Thus, the Germans are again between the two fronts.
They are expected to play a more independent role, but they are not used to it.
I believe that so far they are only groping their role, but are on the way to a “more normal” foreign policy.
A foreign policy that France or the United Kingdom is pursuing.
What exactly does “normal” foreign policy mean from a German point of view?
It is a willingness to take a position independent of the position of the United States or European partners in their national interests.
I believe that German foreign policy depends on economic policies, that is, on exports and ties with certain regions, such as Russia, China or the Middle East.
Germany’s economic interests are largely different from the interests of other major states, and therefore Germany must protect its interests.
Did these economic interests affect the position in the Middle East conflict and the vote in the UN?
First, Germany has major markets in the Middle East, particularly in the Gulf states.
Therefore, it needs to be careful not to offend the public and the elites in the Arab countries.
Either way, it plays a role.
But I wouldn’t give it too much importance, it’s not a completely one-sided connection.
But in any case, it plays an important role in the calculations of the Germans.
Has Germany harmed its relationship with the United States by abstaining in making important decisions, such as the vote on Palestine?
I am sure that in Europe and even the United States, the understanding of the German position prevails.
So I don’t think it was as dramatic as it was in the Libyan question.
Perhaps Germany will even acquire a certain respect in this way.
After all, this signals that it should be taken seriously as a player in the international arena and that its interests should be considered.
There are different views in Europe about the Palestinian initiative.
The United States, on the contrary, was clearly in favor of the veto.
Is there a divergence of views between the United States and many European states?
Due to American domestic policy, such differences have always existed.
I believe that the Obama government has a sufficient understanding of the European position.
But due to the local political situation, the government, of course, cannot openly occupy such a position.
I believe that significant differences of opinion are not at all as significant as it always seems.
If you look at the relationship between Obama and Prime Minister Netanyahu, you will notice that Obama is not at all happy with Netanyahu’s policy.
Is it easy for Germany to combine its close ties with Israel and the United States on the one hand and the position of the most important partner in the EU on the other?
I think that’s what makes the situation so difficult for the Germans.
Of course, it would be somewhat easier for the Germans if there was a single, consistent European policy, but now it is not.
They are therefore unable to act as part of a broader approach and are forced instead to act on their own vision of the situation.
This is what they do with the euro.
I think that in the future Germany will take the lead in the development of a common European position.
It is clear that this is not easy for Germany, at least because of ties with Israel.
This topic has always been sensitive.
But I think it is clear to the Germans that they should play a more independent role.
If Germany sees itself as an important international player, will it really take on?
Or is the leading role still difficult for Germany?
Germany is not yet accustomed to this, it is still always unpleasant and, for obvious reasons, it is always difficult to play a significant role.
Consider, for example, the euro crisis - every time Germany takes an important role, a variety of anti-German feelings appear.
The Germans are not just about to cope with this.
Actually, this is an old problem: you don’t want to be surrounded by hostile countries.
From this point of view, Germany is in a much more difficult situation than the United States.
It should take into account a variety of neighbors and opinions, and this is not easy.
So, U.S. influence in European politics is constantly weakening, but at the moment the EU does not fill this vacuum, who then remains?
