Yeah, yeah.
Perhaps we have more in common than I thought.
Old Battles in the New Middle East
Israel-Cross ceasefire agreement and Hamas group could become a fragile foundation for further peace
Is it possible to have a lasting peace between Arabs and Israelis in the Middle East?
Another round of bloodshed pushes to the conclusion that such hopes are futility.
The seemingly lack of debate about who started first; many buildings have been turned into ruins; more than 140 Palestinians have been killed, most of whom were civilians, and six Israelis; for the first time in the conflict, rockets fired from the Gaza Strip have fallen in the vicinity of the Israeli capital Tel Aviv and the holy city of Jerusalem.
However, despite the fact that the Israelis and Palestinians are hopelessly bogged down in their perennial conflict, changes have come to the Middle East.
This can be treated differently, but the events of the “Arab Spring” have been entrenched in a rebellious storm, and the Palestinians and the Israelis failed to stay away from the vortex that shook the region.
Perhaps as a result, their struggle will become even more bloody than before.
However, there are reasons that give hope for a way out of this deadly impasse.
War without winners
At first glance, the current situation does not give rise to optimism.
Even if the ceasefire, which was signed on November 21, will be implemented, the clashes that took place this week only strengthened the positions of the security forces on both sides.
The leaders of the Islamist Hamas movement, who came to power in the Gaza Strip in 2007, will claim that they forced Israel to retreat, despite the losses suffered by them.
Despite the fact that some of the leaders of the group were destroyed, and 1.7 million residents are blocked in one of the most dense and problematic corners of our planet, Israel failed to destroy Hamas.
In fact, Hamas is building up its popularity in the West Bank, another Palestinian territory currently controlled by the More Moderate Fatah Movement.
Moreover, Hamas leaders may well come to the conclusion that time is working for them.
As the influence of Islamist movements in the Arab world grows, Hamas has new influential and rich friends.
Turkey, which was once Israel’s closest ally among Muslim countries, supported Hamas, followed by Qatar, one of the richest and dynamic Gulf States.
The celebrating Hamas supporters say that Israel has created an Islamist crescent over Israel, from Lebanon in the north, ruled by the Hozbollah paramilitary group, to Syria, in which more and more pro-Islamist rebels are about to overthrow the power of Bashar Assad, and further to Jordan, where the king's authorities are threatening the allies of Hamas.
The most significant change in the balance of power in the region occurred on the southern borders of Israel, in the most populous and important Arab country, in Egypt, where under President Mohamed Morsi strengthened the influence of the Muslim Brotherhood.
Hosni Mubarak, who ruled Egypt for 30 years and was overthrown in 2011, was a secular dictator who did not pay special attention to the support of Hamas.
The Muslim Brotherhood, by contrast, is an organization that is largely similar to Hamas, and their leaders are more prone to populism.
In future diplomatic spaces, Hamas can become a significant player whose voice will not be able to drown out even Israel and America.
At the same time, supporters of the “hard” line in Israel will come to opposite conclusions.
In a military sense, Hamas was defeated.
The Israeli Iron Dome anti-missile system justified the cost of creating it and successfully destroyed many of Hamas’s missiles launched.
Israeli citizens can sleep peacefully, at least for a while.
As for diplomacy, the United States remained faithful to its unaltered position; many European countries also blamed the beginning of the last round of violence on Hamas.
Another important factor is the economic prosperity of Israel, especially under the government of Benjamin Netanyahu, which largely ignored the peace process.
Despite the fact that since 2004. Approximately 30 Israelis have died from rockets fired from the Gaza Strip, Israel has been able to minimize the problem of suicide bombers, in part by a wall that enters the territory of the West Bank, a significant part of the unrecognized Palestinian State, and protects Jewish settlements that continue to expand despite the illegality of such actions from international law.
The position of Prime Minister Netanyahu, whose Likud party – in preparation for the January 22 elections – has united with even more aggressive conservatives under the leadership of Avigdor Lieberman, is very convenient.
What is the point of indulging the Palestinians and giving them their own state?
If you give up all the power in the West Bank, will they begin to launch rockets from there to Israel, as their fellow workers in the Gaza Strip do?
It is better to keep them behind the wall and strictly suppress any attempts to raise their heads.
Perhaps supporters of the “hard” line will win; however, their calculations can be refuted in the Arab spring.
Despite the fact that the Islamists who come to power in Egypt and other countries do not experience the warmest feelings for Israel, their priority will be internal problems.
The defense part of Israel’s budget is greater than that of all its Arab neighbors combined.
The outbreak of war with the regional superpower is unlikely to help Arab governments strengthen their own economy.
The pagmatism of the President of Egypt, Morsi, who worked with Barack Obama on a ceasefire, is a good sign and can mark the beginning of change.
Israel must, to no lesser, take into account the long-term consequences of its policies.
As democratic changes come in the Arab countries, depriving the Palestinians of the right to self-determination is a time bomb that will sooner or later explode in Israeli-occupied territories, like a bus blown up in Tel Aviv this week.
Repression is already undermining the foundations of a democratic order in the Jewish state, and the demographic dimension - the rise of the Arab population - only exacerbates these problems.
For the bloody operations, which are carried out every few years in the Gaza Strip to suppress the Hamas movement, it is necessary to pay the growing discontent of the international community.
Both sides need an external impulse
There remains the only solution that is relentlessly called upon by sensible representatives on both sides, as well as most of the rest of the world and our newspaper: the formation of two states and Israel’s concession of territories in exchange for security.
There remains hope, not too impressive in the short term, the hope that a ceasefire will allow other countries to more effectively influence the parties to the conflict.
Egypt, which is long overdue to decide to block arms shipments to the Gaza Strip, as well as Turkey and Qatar, have a lucrative position more than ever to convince Hamas to recognize the borders of the Jewish state, adopted since 1967, taking into account the exchange of territories and the sharing of Jerusalem.
Other Arab countries should also make efforts to reconcile the Hamas and Fatah movements.
This would do more to create a Palestinian state than an upcoming vote at the UN, which could result in the recognition of the virtual statehood of Palestine.
President Obama has to play its part in bringing Israel to the negotiating table.
During his first term, he had not submitted his own peace plan.
After returning to the White House, he still demonstrates the reluctance to join the solution of this problem.
This is a disastrously short-sighted position.
The United States has a vital interest in stability in the Middle East.
This is possible only in the case of a peace agreement between Israel and the Palestinians.
In Australia, the law on unified packaging for cigarettes came into force.
Warnings about the dangers of smoking and the image of the affected body parts are contrasted on dull green boxes, the same for all brands of cigarettes.
The first Australian law in the world on the same type of packaging of cigarettes and tobacco products came into force, replacing the logos and color design of different brands with the same dragon of dull-and-flower color with eerie pictures of body parts affected by the disease and images of children whose health is undermined by smoking by their parents.
In addition to the different pictures and inscriptions warning of the dangers of smoking, the only difference between the packs, introduced mandatory from this Saturday - the names of stamps that are printed in the same small print.
These are the most severe conditions in the world for the registration of tobacco products.
The Australian federal government says the purpose of this measure is to keep young people from smoking, depriving this bad habit of fashionable status.
This decision is based on the results of studies that showed that people who have not started smoking before the age of 26, in 99 cases out of 100 never become smokers.
“Obviously, even at a very young age, children understand the meaning that tobacco companies are trying to convey with the help of packaging,” explains the Minister of Health Tanya Plibersek, referring to studies that showed that, for example, the crown in the logo is associated with the idea of a princess in the logo.
Australia is one of the world’s least share of smokers, so these changes will not particularly affect the profits of transnational corporations, but the possibility of taking such measures is already being considered by other countries.
Representatives of the tobacco industry strongly opposed the adoption of this law.
Tobacco companies claim that this will only increase the share of the black market, which will sell cheap and affordable cigarettes.
“This law will lead to serious consequences other than those that have been conceived by its initiators,” said Scott McIntyre, a spokesman for British American Tobacco in Australia.
Manufacturers of counterfeit products from China and Indonesia will supply much more such goods for sale on the streets of Australia.
