For four euros, Indonesian miners risk their lives and health, dragging 70 kilograms of sulfur to the top of the volcano on steep stony trails
There are people for whom their work is hell, and others literally work in hell.
Among them are Anto Vijaya, one of the 400 miners who earn a living by sulfur mining in the Kawah-Ijang volcano, located in the east of the Indonesian island of Java.
Every day Anto descends to the bottom of the crater, where the sulfur gas rising from the depths of the Earth freezes when in contact with the air.
Coupling huge pieces of sulfur, the total weight of which can reach 70 kg, it puts them in two bamboo baskets, puts baskets on the shoulders and carries them up on a steep stony road.
To the top of the volcano, whose height is 2.386 meters, is only 250 meters, but it takes more than 40 minutes for the emaciated loaders to rise in a turtle step, with difficulty keeping the balance and gently vigilantly groping the road so as not to stumble and not fall off the cliff.
They know that one wrong step could cost them a life, as happened to a tourist from France, who fell off the cliffs of Cavach-Ijen a few years ago.
Chemists from Kavakh-Ijen earn 5 cents for every kilogram of sulfur that is mined
Once upstairs, they pave their way between tourists who photograph them as if they were monkeys from a circus and, it is tired of carrying heavy baskets, walk three kilometers to the scales that the mining company has placed a little higher, at an altitude of 1.850 meters.
We are talking about the RT Kandy Ngrimbi, a plant that has been operating since 1960 this volcano and, it is better and not to say, its employees, with which it pays 662 Indonesian rupees (5 euro cents) for every kilogram of sulfur.
It then sells it for 10,000 rupees (83 euro cents) to petrochemical production, because this mineral is common in everyday life and is used to make matches, fireworks, cosmetics, dynamite and even for sugar whitening.
“Since the norm is the carrier of 70 kilograms, we earn about 46,000 rupees (3.8 euros) for each walk,” explains Anto, who usually performs three daily transfers.
He spends three hours on each of them and at the end feels broken, but they allow him to accumulate 138,000 rupees (11.5 euros) by the end of the day.
Although it seems like a miser for such an inhuman effort, it is three times more than what he would earn in the field.
“The fee for miners is very high by local standards, where 15,000 rupees (1.2 euros) are paid for coffee collection (1.2 euros) per day and the average monthly earnings are equal to two million rupees (167 euros),” explains the loader who used to work as a bricklayer on the tourist island of Bali.
There, his salary was 75,000 rupees (6.2 euros) a day and the plot was not as heavy, but Anto returned with his family to Banyuvangi, a town near a volcano, for a good reason, which in Indonesia is as crushing as sulfur: "I married a girl with Bali, where some Hindus, and brought her to Java so that she would accept Islam."
In Anto asthma, he breathes with difficulty, constantly coughs, and his eyes get watered because of toxic gases
At the age of 27, Anto spent three years, risking himself in Kawah-Ijen, whose sero has already begun to affect him despite the presence of a mask and special glasses.
He has asthma, he breathes with difficulty, constantly coughs, and his eyes get watered because of the toxic gases that the volcano emits.
This is the price he has to pay to achieve his dream.
“I will work for another two years because I want to open a store or study Spanish or French,” he promises in more than acceptable English.
Punished by life, this pleasant and intelligent young man could be a tourist guide, waiter or a porter at the hotel, but instead he does the work of a mule.
Divide a dirty wooden hut with other porters, it rises every day at two o'clock in the morning, because sulfur does not cease to leak out at night, when its characteristic yellow color turns into blue and shines among the darkness.
Challenging the shadows, Anto descends into the crater, illuminating his way with a small flashlight connected to his helmet, which he himself bought with his own money.
About 400 porters drag baskets with sulfur on their shoulders from the bottom of the volcano
Despite high profits, the mining company has not mechanized sulfur mining to save costs and does not provide any equipment to porters who work in their account and with such deprivations.
In fact, they don’t even get parts of 30,000 rupees (2.5 euros) collection for photography, which, along with an entrance ticket for 15,000 rupees (1.2 euros), the guards of this reserve charge tourists who come to take a picture of the volcano and its mules.
“This work is for livestock, not for people,” says Badrusin, a 42-year-old stocked porter who spent three decades in Kawah-Jeden since he left college.
Able to raise up to 110 kilograms, he assures that he will tolerate the work “as much as he can” because he needs money to educate his three children aged 18 to 10 years.
I'm not going to retire, I'll die here because the volcano is my whole life
Although sulfur burns the throat and burns the eyes, when the wind suddenly changes and catches miners in the tight pillars of smoke coming out of the volcano, they are so hardy that none complains about their serious diseases. more serious, obviously, than their usual breathing problems, arthrosis, knee pain and ulcers on the shoulders, which were deformed under the weight of the baskets.
Balancing the basket on the back, Unaynik can now only lift 50 kilograms in his 53 years.
Every day, he and his comrades take out 15 tons of sulfur from a volcano that three trucks transport to a warehouse in Tamansari, covering a distance of 18 kilometers along a narrow path among thickets.
“I’m not going to retire, I’ll die here because the volcano is my whole life,” Unaynik said, opening a mouth wide that lacks a few teeth.
Of his five children, the eldest, 30 years old, also works as a sulfur carrier.
Time passes, but poverty perpetuates from generation to generation one of the most difficult activities in the world: what human mules from Kawah-Ijen do.
