On FB I upload beautiful pictures or pictures from games.
I also have fun with my friends.
“I wouldn’t share a photo that’s not mine or someone who behaves stupidly,” he says.
The boy realizes that it is bad to publish indecent photos of naked people, crimes or to write offensive or furious comments.
Jorge says he knows 35 friends at his FB and nine followers on Twitter.
Most of them are relatives.
Mother knows, she has a password to one of the accounts.
I started Twitter to express myself and write interesting tweets.
“I don’t know if they’re answering me, I’m just loading them,” he adds.
“Social networks are entertainment, I can talk to distant relatives or with my friends in a quick way,” he points out.
Without hesitation, he answers that he would never have accepted a request from an unfamiliar person.
I wouldn’t reckon with someone who would recommend it to a stranger.
The case of 14-year-old Jose is different.
This teenager has open accounts on Hotmail, Facebook, My Space and Ask, and in the latter admits that he does not know 20 people added to his friend list.
“It doesn’t scare me because we have something in common, music, for example,” he says.
According to the boy, no one trusted him and did not ask for his home address or phone number.
“If they put pressure or demand on me, I’ll just remove them from my account,” he admits.
Jose became a follower of Ask after reading the recommendation on Twitter.
The boy is not alien to the experience of what is known today as a cyber-mobbing.
A friend of my friend was blackmailed on the social network.
He was threatened and excavated with money.
“He never found out who it was,” he assures.
The victim, according to José, did not delete the account.
“Only included confidentiality.”
Then he explains the sequence of steps to configure the account in a secure manner.
Unlike Jorge, this boy would upload photos of acquaintances in uncomfortable or embarrassing situations.
Yes, I would do it if I don't like a person or if I want it.
“Although I know it’s cybermobbing,” he said.
Key issues
Marieros Porras, an English teacher and a specialist in education and training, believes that in order to guide children and adolescents, you need to understand that the purpose of social networks is to inform.
“The Internet appeared as a means to search for information, but with the advent of these sites, the rules of the game have changed,” she notes.
Porras points out that academician Mark Prensky, a master of pedagogy from Yale University and author of Labor Digital Aborigines and Immigrants, invented these terms to explain this phenomenon.
Digital aborigines are they, children and young people who were born in the era of technology.
“We are digital immigrants who have to teach them, while we are still learning,” she says.
Explains that this topic is complex, “because we ask them to have a certain criterion of what can or cannot be distributed, published or spoken, at an age when maturity is not enough for it.”
“Also that they are selective, while the most important thing for them to be popular is to have thousands of friends without thinking about the consequences,” she adds.
According to the expert, the most effective way to show what privacy is for children and adolescents is to ask questions that make them reflect.
“To tell them not to do it is useless,” she adds.
Then Porras lists some options: There are things that you would not tell a stranger, so why are you doing it online?
Or would you like it if you posted a photo of you like the one you posted about your friend?
Do you know what others are posting about you?
When you sign pictures from parties, do you ask for permission from other people to celebrate them?
And one more thing, do everyone need to know what you do at every moment?
Another point is to let them know that they have to behave online as they do offline.
The rules are the same.
“Outside the Internet, a person behaves with respect, responsibility and other principles, so should be on social networks,” she says.
Vigilance
Estuardo Guardia, a university lecturer, professor of primary education and a counsellor on education, explains the need for heads of families to read social media policies in good faith.
By understanding each of the items, they have good reasons for talking with children about the prerequisites for opening an account on the Internet.
“For example, age and what is allowed to be distributed or published,” he says.
According to Gaurdia, the key issue is to remind children of the lesson “do not talk to strangers.”
UNASUR summit ends without promulgation of the Lima Declaration
The 5th Presidential Summit of the Union of South American Nations (UNASUR) ended today in Peru without the promulgation of the Lima Declaration, previously and theoretically signed by seven mandatory participants.
Efe has repeatedly tried to access the document signed at the VI next meeting of Heads of State and Government of National University, but sources from the Office and the Presidential Administration indicated on the homepage that it would be transmitted after closure, but then confirmed that it would be published on the Peruvian Government website at some point.
To questions about the text, they pointed out that the content was stated by the President of Peru, Olalt Umala, during brief statements for the press.
Journalists’ access to information about the Summit was always limited.
During the day, only was broadcast, in the press hall, video of the presidential assembly without the sound with the message "closed meeting, sound is prohibited."
The little information circulated among reporters was provided by the press secretary of some UNASUR governments attending the meeting, but not Peruvian.
The only document circulated during the day was a list of participating presidents, which caused discontent among hundreds of journalists from various national and international media who asked for more information.
Subsequently, the administration of the President of Peru sent an electronic media message with the “final declaration” of the summit, but we are talking about the statement of Umala, and not about the official document, which ended the summit.
Last October, Peru hosted the 3rd South American and Arab Summit (ASPA), and at that time, despite the fact that the press insistently required, the so-called Lima Declaration, which was previously announced, was also not distributed.
On the official website of ASPA, you can check that the document was published last Tuesday.
At both international meetings, the Peruvian authorities tried to ensure that transmission systems were provided for all journalists, but would limit the receipt of information as much as possible.
The summit also ended with a joint decision by Chile and Peru to accept the verdict of the Hague Court, which will resolve the territorial dispute between the two countries.
The presidents of Peru, Oliantha Umala, and Chile, Sebastian Piñera, gathered at a regional meeting and ratified that they would abide by the International Court of Justice, which begins hearing statements by both sides in Auge Monday, as part of the charges that Lima had put forward against Santiago.
“We will abide by and implement a decision that will clarify the differences that we are currently presenting to this international court,” Umala said.
“Chile was, is and will be a country that respects international law, peaceful resolution of differences, pacts and international tribunals,” Pinier added, and greeted Umalu’s hands against the backdrop of the flags of these two countries.
The confirmation by both presidents of the fact that they would obey the International Court of Justice came as soon as Colombia appealed this week to the Bogotá Pact, according to which it recognized the subordination of the verdicts of this international court after the decision on maritime borders with Nicaragua, which it considered erroneous.
The summit took place in the absence of the presidents of Brazil, Dilma Rousseff; Venezuela, Hugo Chavez; Bolivia, Evo Morales; and Argentina, Christina Kirchner.
Paraguay, whose membership in NATOSUR has been suspended since 2011 after the impeachment of its former president, Fernando Lugo, did not participate in the meeting.
The host president, Ollianta Umalala, was responsible for opening discussions in the morning and for closing the summit, a little later than noon Limsky time.
The head of state read the final document, which reported that 16 agreements were adopted and the directions of action on 31 projects among South American countries were approved, the amount of the expected investment amounted to $ 17 billion.
Among the agreements adopted, he mentioned that UNASUR countries will take “important steps towards the goal of South American citizenship, for which we are expanding the residency agreements.”
He said that action was being taken to improve “cooperation in the fight against citizens’ insecurity and against organized transnational crime, actions to increase the availability of medicines, low-cost Internet access in all corners of South America and to take into account the cumulative and effective risks of natural disasters.”
Since Europe is in crisis, “the economic union (Latin America) should not have a triumphant foundation, but should serve to expand our production foundation and anticipate a better future for our cities,” Umala added.
“We have decided to give privileges to a group of 31 landmark projects that will improve the connection of the spaces of South America, especially in the rustic and border zones. uniting our countries and forming new economic schemes,” the Peruvian president said in a read message.
Among these projects, he mentioned that five belonged to Peru, and were limited to cross-axles on its territory, from the coast to Brazil, and the two were aiming for a large link with Ecuador, but it did not provide more details.
The final document also touched upon the political situation in Paraguay.
“We hope that the electoral process in this country will serve its re-accession to the Union of South American Nations”, from which it is currently excluded.
The need for Latin America to remain a region of prosperity and peace would be united, and have good relations between neighbours, was another topic emphasized at the summit.
In this sense, Colombian President Juan Manuel Santos said before proceeding to participate in a regional meeting that he hopes to meet with his Nicaraguan counterpart, Daniel Ortega, on Saturday in Mexico City for negotiations in a respectful form of maritime dispute as a result of the verdict of an international court dispute contested by Bogota.
“The day after tomorrow, maybe I’ll meet with President Daniel Ortega,” Santos said.
“We will revise all these paths, they are not mutually exclusive, including the pact with Nicaragua will require discussion with Nicaragua,” he said.
“I hope I can tell him President President that we will be able to cope with this as possible civilized and respectfully as possible,” Santos added.
Santos and Ortega will meet on Saturday in Mexico City, where they have the presence of a new president of that country, Enrique Peña Nieto, in office.
Also within the framework of the summit, the defense ministers of the bloc tentatively met for approval of the Action Plan for 2013, which is aimed at strengthening dialogue and unanimity on the issue of protecting the region.
Argentina, Bolivia, Colombia, Ecuador, Peru, Brazil, Uruguay, Chile, Chile, Guyana, Suriname and Paraguay form UNASUR, although the latter's participation has been suspended.
Peru has a provisional presidency in the regional bloc.
