Fabrizio was 21 years old when he was told that his AIDS test had yielded positive results.
“It’s like I’ve been drowned out,” he recalls that difficult, despite the whole doctor’s beat, the moment.
The young man hid it from his family.
Deciding to cope with the disease on his own, he wanted to learn about it as much as possible. And his efforts were fulfilled - he has already celebrated his 43 th birthday.
Fabrizio is one of the “oldest” patients of the hospital Hospital Civil de Guadalajara (HCG), where he got in 1994, overcoming many obstacles.
He has been living with a diagnosis of human immunodeficiency virus (HIV) for 22 years. In the early 90-ies it would be difficult to believe - too few treatment options existed at that time, too little knew about the disease, too biased against patients.
So, even the director of the clinic of the Mexican Institute of Social Protection did not want to say goodbye to him, "because he had a cut."
In other words, in those days, having AIDS was a sentence.
Now it is possible to survive this syndrome and do it without worsening the quality of life.
However, not knowing about their illness, so far many people come when the virus has already caused damage, “depleted” their immune system and they suffer from opportunistic infections.
31 years after the introduction of AIDS in the world, at least after the first reported cases, “a great achievement at the moment is that the survival of a patient who starts treatment in a timely manner and the survival of the general population is exactly the same,” said the head of the HIV department of HCG, Jaime Andre Viljanueva, citing the fact that this information was confirmed in April this year in a prestigious scientific publication.
Infectious and HIV/AIDS expert, Andrade Viljanueva, explained that since 2008, scientists have concluded that AIDS is not a sentence, but the duration and quality of life depend on the degree of damage to the immune system available in patients at the beginning of the diagnosis, with the best life expectancy of those who do not use drugs: up to 30 years with CD4, and up to 50 years, when reported 500 CD4.
Simply put, the above means that someone who receives a diagnosis of HIV-positive at the age of 25, according to these terms, “supporting control, will be able to live without problems up to 75 years,” he explained.
To assess this progress, it should be remembered that the life expectancy of Mexicans today is an average of 76 years.
Although mortality has declined significantly in recent years, in the case of Mexico, the number of people dying from AIDS has decreased from 6,678 in 2007 to 4,862 in 2011 (UNAIDS’ annual report), it is also true that 60 per cent of patients in the national database have died since AIDS in the advent.
In Jalisco alone, 255 people died in 2011, and 187 deaths by May of this year have already been reported; however, it is claimed that there is widespread access to antiretroviral drugs since 2005.
- Why are there still fatalities?
- Personally, it seems to me that the problem is not in access to treatment.
So I imagine it, this is how things are in our hospital.
At least the last 12 years we have not had a lack of medicines, the problem is that patients come very late, because they do not know about their infected state, that is, in the late stages of the disease.
He cited devastating data: “nine out of ten patients come when they already have some opportunistic infection; what needs to be done to have a greater impact on overall mortality is to conduct a diagnosis at an earlier stage, and therefore it is necessary to provide samples for detection on a massive scale, for all people who will ask for it.”
In their proposal, experts and officials of the State AIDS Prevention Council in Jalisco (COESA) agree on their proposal, as well as the patients themselves, like Fabrizio, who turned to a private laboratory, motivated only by the fact that his friend did it and, despite his young age, he was already at the stage of AIDS and even suffered from Kaposi's sarcoma, a cancerous tumor.
Everything changes when you know you have AIDS.
